    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:08f8bbc9-581e-4b6f-956a-42c3d4f0bf49",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a bright-eyed, 5-year-old girl from Brno, Czech Republic, who attends kindergarten and loves drawing, playing with her toy animals, and chasing her older brother around the family's small garden. She is brought to the paediatric clinic by her mother on a chilly late-winter morning, wrapped in a colourful scarf. Her cheeks are slightly flushed and her eyes are watery, giving her a visibly uncomfortable appearance.\n\n{patientName} presents with a two-day history of nasal congestion [SNOMED:J00], runny nose [MEDLINEPLUS:J00], sore throat [SNOMED:J00, MEDLINEPLUS:J00], and an irritating cough [SNOMED:J00, MEDLINEPLUS:J00]. Her mother reports that she has been sneezing repeatedly since yesterday [MEDLINEPLUS:J00] and complains of a headache [SNOMED:J00, MEDLINEPLUS:J00]. She has had a low-grade fever since last night [SNOMED:J00], and while she is not in severe distress, she has been more irritable than usual [SNOMED:J00] and slept poorly, occasionally snoring [SNOMED:J00].\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with her parents and a 9-year-old brother in a flat near the city centre. Her brother had a similar cold about a week ago, which is consistent with person-to-person viral transmission through close contact [MEDLINEPLUS:J00]. She attends a local kindergarten five days a week, where respiratory illnesses circulate frequently, especially in winter and spring [MEDLINEPLUS:J00]. She eats well overall but has had a reduced appetite over the past day.\n\nHer mother is attentive and well-informed, asking the doctor whether antibiotics are needed. The doctor reassures her that the common cold is caused by viruses — most often rhinoviruses — and that treatment is symptomatic and supportive [MEDLINEPLUS:J00]. {patientName} is cooperative during examination, though she grimaces when the doctor inspects her throat."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d358444f-2251-422a-ab27-2e1b8451e6a5",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
